
[MODULE:MASTER THE CORE ELEMENT OF PERFORMANCE -SPRINT:ENERGY IN THE BODY AND MIND]
MENTAL energy analysis
Tool explanation and guide – FOR REVIEW ONLY
[01/05]
TOOL PREVIEW
Type of tool: Individual tool
Suggested preparation time: 20 minutes 

[02/05]
Purpose  
Why this tool matters
This tool is designed to bring clarity to your priorities by focusing on what you can control. By understanding your capacity to impact certain aspects of your life, you can channel your energy toward meaningful actions.

The second part of the tool will help you analyze the gap between your reactions to events and your ideal responses. It promotes self-awareness and enables behavioral adjustments, which are critical for personal growth and achieving emotional resilience. Understanding the gap between your initial emotional reactions and your desired responses is a powerful way to improve emotional intelligence. The second part of the tool gives you insight into your patterns and empowers you to make conscious changes.

Outcome you can expect
A clearer focus on actionable tasks and behaviors leads to greater satisfaction and less stress.

The second part of the tool will provide you with a clearer understanding of your emotional triggers, improved responses to challenging situations, and a roadmap for better emotional regulation.
[03/05]
Step-by-Step Instructions
part 1 
1. Define what matters to you
List things that matter to you and that you have control over.  
List things that matter to you and that you DO NOT have control over.
2. Decide what you will stop doing
Identify three things to stop doing completely.
3. Decide what you will do less
List three things you will do less of starting today, focusing on behaviors that don't add value.
4. Decide what you will do more of
Choose three actions that you will commit to doing more of starting today.
part 2 
1. Reflect on an event
Think about a recent event where your reaction wasn't aligned with how you would have ideally responded.

Example of a Correct Answer: "I reacted angrily to feedback during a meeting."
2. Analyze the Gap
Identify the difference between your reaction and the response you would have preferred. Reflect on what caused the gap.

Example of a Correct Answer: "I wish I had stayed calm and asked for clarification instead of reacting emotionally."
3. Plan for future responses
Based on your analysis, plan how you will handle similar situations in the future to achieve a better outcome.

Example of a Correct Answer: "Next time, I’ll pause before responding and ask more questions."
[04/05]

mistakes to avoid
1. Being too hard on yourself.
The goal is improvement, not perfection. Focus on growth, not punishment.
2. Avoiding uncomfortable situations.
Facing your emotional triggers is the only way to grow. Be honest in your reflections.
[05/05]


f.a.q. and answers

1. What if I can't think of a specific event?
Reflect reflect on smaller, everyday moments where your reaction didn’t align with your values or goals.

